snippet.textDisplay:
For six hundred years we have sung this song in our part of the world, and it remains a song of ethereal and undiminished beauty.

Amir Khusrow has to have been the very first poet/author of note writing in Hindi. Here Abida Parveen and Rahat Fateh Ali Khan do him full justice.

I first heard this song as a child in a street outside the mazaar of Moinuddin Chisti in Ajmer, and I remember that moment very well.

Thank you for making me remember again.

snippet.textDisplay:
Ohh! I came here through some of the great musicians of the Indian subcontinent and found 1947 partition completely absurd. 

I am from Bangladesh and started listening Lalon tonight as a routine approach. Then through Arko Mukherjee, Abida Parveen, Rahat Fateh Ali Khan, Saieen Zahoor and many other artists; I was fortunate to know Bulleh Shah. After listening to some kalam (as it's said), I can relate Bulleh Shah to Lalon Shah. Probably, Bulleh Shah turned into Lalon in his afterlife :) 

We (Pak, Ind, Bang) were blessed with Sufism but throughout the time, we couldn't handle the fanaticism that was initiated by the British. Then came 1947 partition and more violence ....

snippet.textDisplay:
As it my preferred song in Coke Studio, I transformed the listening of this song into  "daily ritual".It just transmits a very colorful mood, a perceptual bliss into me.
Perhaps all the translations to any other language other than the original (Urdu?)  cannot captivate the inner meaning of it.
These artists renditions can expresss more than the words.

Wkipedia:
The modified version of this song is also featured in Raj Khosla's 1978 
release "Main Tulsi Tere Aangan Ki' sung by Lata Mangeshkar and Asha Bhosle, composed by Laxmikant Pyarelal.
 This song has also made its place in the musical TV shows such as Sa Re
 Ga Ma Pa, Chote Ustaad etc. where various contestants such as Richa 
Sharma, Abhijeet Shrivastva, Harshdeep Kaur and once a judge also (Daler Mehndi) have mesmerised the audiences by singing this song. A version also featured in Coke Studio sung by Abida Parveen and Rahat Fateh Ali Khan.[5] An Indian fusion band Mast Qalandars with The Peninsula Studios published a new[6] rendition of this song on Jan 7, 2014 on YouTube. The song was also sung by Shruti Pathak in a collaboration with Hriday Gattani.
